<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_HarmonicSeries"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport xmlns="" href="../Analysis_TeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	  <title>Harmonic Series: Example</title>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>Determine if the harmonic series below convergences to a number.
				
			</para.body>
            <index.glossary>
               <term>harmonic</term>
               <term>series</term>
               <info>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Demonstration that this series does not converge to a number.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </info>
            </index.glossary>
         </para>
			      <math.display xmlns="">
				        <latex>1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \cdots + \dfrac{1}{n} + \cdots</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme xmlns="">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The summands of the given series satisfy</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>\lim_{n\to \infty} \dfrac{1}{n}\ =\ 0</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>So through the eyes of the proposition which says: ‘If <math>
                        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} a_n=L\in\RNr</latex>
                     </math>, then <math>
                        <latex>\lim_{n\to\infty}a_n = 0</latex>
                     </math>’, it is possible that the series converges to a number. Remarkable is, however, that this is not so. Instead the harmonic series converges to <math>
                        <latex>+\infty</latex>
                     </math>. To see this, partition segments of the series as follows:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
1+\dfrac{1}{2}\ +\ \underset{ &gt; 1/2 }{\left( \dfrac{1}{3} + \dfrac{1}{4}\right) }\ +\ \underset{ &gt; 1/2 }{\left( \dfrac{1}{5} + \dfrac{1}{6}+\dfrac{1}{7} + \dfrac{1}{8}\right) } + \cdots + \underset{ &gt; 1/2 }{\left( \dfrac{1}{2^n+1} +\cdots+ \dfrac{1}{2^{n+1}}\right) + \cdots }
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This means that the partial sum</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
s_{2^n} &gt; (n+1)\cdot \dfrac{1}{2}
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The sequence of partial sums is strictly increasing, and so</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>\lim_{k\to\infty} s_k = \lim_{n\to\infty}s_{2^n} = \lim_{n\to \infty} \dfrac{n+1}{2} = +\infty</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We interpret this example by saying ‘the summands of the harmonic series converge to slowly to <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> to allow the series to converge to a number’.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
